<taxonomicName authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2007" box="[331,476,1491,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pythamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montanus">
<emphasis box="[331,476,1491,1516]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">P. montanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the Palni Hills. Illustrations provided by both 
<bibRefCitation author="Pruthi, H. S." box="[1277,1435,1490,1516]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" pagination="69 - 99" refId="ref4584" refString="Pruthi, H. S. 1934. Studies on Indian Jassidae (Homoptera). Part II. Description of the genotypes of some of the genera founded by W. L. Distant, with a revision of the genus Moonia Distant. Memoirs of the Indian Museum, 11, 69 - 99." type="journal article" year="1934">Pruthi (1934)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Datta, B." box="[205,351,1530,1556]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" pagination="102 - 108" refId="ref4313" refString="Datta, B. 1972. On Indian Cicadellidae (Homoptera) - VI. Zoologischer Anzeinger, Leipzig, 189, 102 - 108." type="journal article" year="1972">Datta (1972</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Datta, B." box="[368,428,1530,1556]" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" refId="ref4339" refString="Datta, B. 1988. On Oriental Cicadellidae (Homoptera: Insecta). Miscellaneous Publication, Occasional Paper No. 90, xiv + 256 pp. Records of the Zoological Survey of India." type="book" year="1988">1988</bibRefCitation>
) clearly show that the male specimens illustrated are of this species where as the females are of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2007" box="[327,481,1571,1596]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pythamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bispinosus">
<emphasis box="[327,481,1571,1596]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">P. bispinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It can be easily distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melichar" authorityYear="1903" box="[1110,1226,1571,1596]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pythamus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1110,1226,1571,1596]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="57">Pythamus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its short basal processes of the aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
